  abstract={This article expresses concern with the unprecedented attack on “pseudohistory” that this journal (Critical Review of History) presented in cooperation with dozens of professional historians in three consecutive issues. While acknowledging the harms done by some aggressive extra-institutional historians to professional research, I argue that using the term “pseudohistory” to refer to objects rather than ascribe a property to already demarcated objects has undesirable epistemic, prudential, and ethical consequences for the study of Korean antiquity.}
